%I A352029 #21 Apr 11 2026 16:05:05
%S A352029 1,1,2,2,2,14,204,7
%N A352029 a(n) is the number of minimalist polyominoes that can contain all n-ominoes.
%C A352029 a(n) is the number of free polyominoes that can contain all n-ominoes and that have size A327094(n), which is the minimum size for such a polyomino.
%C A352029 From _Peter Exley_, Apr 06 2026: (Start)
%C A352029 a(8) = 7, proved by exhaustive SAT enumeration over all 36 valid bounding box partitions of 20 cells. The solver uses Counter-Example Guided Abstraction Refinement (CEGAR) with Glucose 4.2. All 7 minimalist containers are in bounding boxes 4 X 8 (6 solutions) and 5 X 8 (1 solution).
%C A352029 The sequence is not monotonic: a(7) = 204 >> a(8) = 7. This is caused by the exponential growth of A000105(n) (free n-ominoes) overwhelming the sub-quadratic growth of A327094(n) (minimum container size), creating extreme constraint density. At n=8, 369 pieces must fit in just 20 cells (density 18.5 pieces/cell vs 6.4 at n=7).
%C A352029 a(9) >= 111. All 111 known solutions are in bounding boxes 5 X 9 (10), 6 X 9 (97), 6 X 10 (1), and 7 X 9 (3).
%C A352029 Independently verified by two verifiers with disjoint code paths (matrix-based and complex-number orientations), both with local-optimality checks.
%C A352029 (End)
%H A352029 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A352029">Solver code, figures, and data</a>, GitHub.
%H A352029 John Mason, <a href="/A352029/a352029.pdf">Illustrations of minimalist container polyominoes</a>
%e A352029 From _Peter Exley_, Apr 06 2026: (Start)
